name: Good Days
lyrics:

annotations:
[('Good day in my mind, safe to take a step out', [['Following the release of the Good Days Fan Video, SZA took to the comments to share her meaning behind the line:

Good days is a mantra, More than than a belief.
Good days is about not being sure .. not Sure hope is still a thing, not sure better is coming, not sure any of even it matters . its an acknowledgement were all in the same ugly chaotic beautiful existence . Shared energy . We‚Äôre all  shattered and stretched beyond our means in all Ways.  Good days is a reminder we‚Äôre all struggling find and feel A Connection. To believe everyday has the tiniest possibility to be better than the last is what It‚Äôs all about. Possibility !! A SLIVER of hope.. not even a whole lot.  A reminder to OURSELVES .. that a sliver is sometimes all u need . I wanna say thank you for sharing your life w me . Your emotions , your darkness, and light. For crying and laughing and committing to being in the moment w me . It‚Äôs hard and I‚Äôm proud of you . love you beyond measure and Thank you for contributing to one of The greatest moments of my life . I never wanna stop Creating and Sharing moments w you ‚Ä¶ even if they suck ‚Ä¶even if Good days aren‚Äôt on the horizon .. I‚Äôm honored to spend them with you‚Ä¶ forever love !
P.S. OFFICIAL GOOD DAYS MUSIC VIDEO WILL BE OUT ASAP !']]), ('Too soon, I spoke
 You be heavy in my mind, can you get the heck out?', [['In the previous line, SZA seems to be in a good headspace. However, this doesn‚Äôt last long when she is reminded of her previous lover. She can‚Äôt stop thinking about them, but she wishes she could.']]), ('Get some air now, let yo edge out', [['This verse captures the complex and relatable sentiment that rest is often justified but simultaneously difficult to embrace. Accordingly, SZA could be using the word ‚Äúedge‚Äù here in a couple of ways. For instance, letting one‚Äôs edge out may refer to allowing oneself to relax or feel relief. It could also refer to ‚Äúedges‚Äù: small fly-away hairs that might be pressed onto the forehead with gel. Here, she gives herself permission to relax, to release the edges from their binding gel. Both meanings in this potential double entendre illustrate the idea that relief is difficult to maintain in the face of ‚Äúheavy‚Äù, intolerable emotions. In this line, she claims that she is relieved before admitting in the following line that she spoke too soon.']]), ('I don‚Äôt miss no ex, I don‚Äôt miss no text
 I choose not to respond', [["SZA most popularly once ignored a text from WESTSIDE BOOGIE, as he details on his song, ‚ÄúSelf Destruction.‚Äù

‚ÄòTil the time I fuck a singer, I can‚Äôt say that I‚Äôm that guy
Like that night I drunk text SZA, she ain‚Äôt reply, whoa

WESTSIDE BOOGIE also breaks down the significance of the verses and what happened the night when he messaged SZA:

I'ma tell y'all the SZA story, and it‚Äôs gonna be the first, probably, and only time I say it. So I was at Coachella, right. I was with my big homie G-Weeder, and I saw SZA. He got a close relationship with TDE because he like big in the streets. He introduces me. And that whole night, because she told me she fuck with my music, the whole night he told me, like, ‚ÄúBro, I feel like you could pull her, bro.‚Äù He gassing me up like, ‚ÄúBro, I feel like you can get SZA. I want somebody to get her.‚Äù Like, he‚Äôs telling me. Like, no disrespect to SZA, because she a queen, but you feel me that night, I left Coachella, I text her like, I think I said something about her music, how I‚Äôm a fan. She told me she fuck with my music too. Then the next message was like, me just trying to link. It wasn‚Äôt any like super, super thirst. In my mind, I was being thirsty, like if we link, I‚Äôm gonna try to slide on her, but I played it cool like I‚Äôm just trying to link with you and work, but she didn‚Äôt reply to me, so. Shout out to SZA, though. That‚Äôs still my dog.
I hope I didn‚Äôt blow my chance for a feature with SZA by being thirsty. That‚Äôs just a reality."]]), ('You‚Äôve been making me feel like I‚Äôm', [['Jacob Collier interpolates this line from his August 2020 track ‚ÄúIn Too Deep,‚Äù which features fellow American R&B singer-songwriter Kiana Led√©:

You been making me feel like I‚Äôm lonely, baby
I don‚Äôt know what I did wrong']]), ('Half of us layin‚Äô waste to our youth, it‚Äôs in the present
 (Na-na, na-na, na-na, na)
 Half of us chasin‚Äô fountains of youth and it‚Äôs in the present now', [['These lines could allude to last track of CTRL ‚Äú20 Somethings,‚Äù which addresses the feelings of discouragement due to growing into adulthood. SZA now emphasizes the value of recognizing your youth and enjoying it despite growing into older age.']]), ('My cross to bear alone, I', [['The phrase cross to bear  refers to a burden or trial that one must endure, alluding to the cross carried by Jesus on the way to his own crucifixion. However SZA has no aid in dealing with the weight of her emotional burden as she carries it alone.']]), ('Said, ‚ÄúNot tryna be a nuisance, this is urgent‚Äù
 Tryna make sense of loose change', [['SZA creates a clever play on words by using the using the homophones ‚Äúsense" and ‚Äúcents.‚Äù  She implies that she is trying to understand the sporadic and minimal communication her lover has given her. This lack of contact represents ‚Äúloose change,‚Äù a combination here of coins and partial understanding. A similar double meaning appears on the chorus to DJ Quik‚Äôs 1995 hit ‚ÄúDollaz + Sense‚Äù:

If it don‚Äôt make dollars, it don‚Äôt make sense

Regardless of SZA‚Äôs efforts to add up the pieces, she still cannot come up with the complete, total amount. As a result, she needs to have a conversation as soon as possible to stop from  overthinking.']]), ('All the while, I‚Äôll await my armored fate with a smile', [['SZA calls her fate ‚Äúarmored‚Äù because she is trying to get herself behind the idea that no one has authority over her future: it is protected. All she can do is be happy with what she has because there is nothing she can control about tomorrow except how she feels.

In an interview with the Breakfast Club, about her previous album Ctrl, she said:

If you try to control a future moment, it‚Äôs impossible. There‚Äôs no such thing as control anyway. It‚Äôs just a concept, a word, a fantasy. But if you focus on the way you feel in the now and what you do with the now, I feel like it leads to having true control in the future.



SZA in an interview with the Breakfast Club. Charlamagne tha God is on the left. 


SZA confirmed the lyric on twitter writing:
https://twitter.com/sza/status/1302673765806100480?s=20']]), ('Feelin‚Äô like, yeah (On your own)
 Feelin‚Äô like Jericho', [['This lyric is a reference to the Battle of Jericho in the biblical Book of Joshua in which the Israelites marched around the city-state of Jericho, persevering until its walls fell down.

SZA uses this simile to describe that her safety or sense of control is falling just like the walls of Jericho.']])]

Being unable to move limbs or speak are common symptoms of sleep paralysis. annotations:
[('Meet you for coffee at the elementary schools', [['In this and the following line, Lana sets up a juxtaposition between youth and maturity. Coffee is typically an adult drink, but she enjoys it by the juvenility of an elementary school. Similarly, the ‚Äúsummer gets cool‚Äù represents an end to the newness of summer as autumn, symbolizing old age, sets in. These lines are about how Lana holds onto her youthful freedom even as she settles into adult life.

This could be a reference to AA meetings, which usually serve coffee and are hosted in public buildings like churches and schools.']]), ('It‚Äôs never too late, baby, so don‚Äôt give up
 It‚Äôs never too late, baby, so don‚Äôt give up', [['‚ÄúIt‚Äôs never too late‚Äù is a recurring theme in some of Lana‚Äôs music. It is most notably present in her 2017 single ‚ÄúSummer Bummer‚Äù with A$AP ROCKY and Playboi Carti. Here, she sings:

It‚Äôs never too late
To leave if you wanna leave (Better Not)
Or to stay if you wanna stay

On ‚ÄúChemtrails Over The Country Club‚Äù, Lana expresses similar sentiments, describing the uncertainty of love and the fragility, or perhaps superficiality, of summer flings. However, this time, she‚Äôs willing to keep love alive, no matter how unlikely the situation may seem.']]), ('The Brentwood Market', [['This line is a reference to the Brentwood Country Mart, a local shopping village in Los Angeles.

Del Rey mentioned the shopping village in an interview with Annie Mac on January 11th, 2021, where she explained:

If I go to the Brentwood Country Mart barefoot or whatever, it‚Äôs like, I‚Äôm not insane, I‚Äôm connected to the earth. Whatever it may be.‚Äù']]), ('I‚Äôm not unhinged or unhappy, I‚Äôm just wild', [['On the Paradise song ‚ÄúRide‚Äù back in 2012, she called herself:

I‚Äôm tired of feeling like I‚Äôm fucking crazy
I‚Äôm tired of driving ‚Äòtil I see stars in my eyes
All I‚Äôve got to keep myself sane, baby
So I just ride, I just ride



And on the Norman Fucking Rockwell! cut ‚Äúhope is a dangerous thing for a woman like me to have ‚Äì but i have it‚Äù, she sings the lines:

Don‚Äôt ask if I‚Äôm happy
You know that I‚Äôm not
But at best you can see I‚Äôm not sad



In Chemtrails Over the Country Club, she seems to be continuing to discover more about herself and finding a balance between the two extremes.']]), ('We‚Äôre in our jewels in the swimming pool', [["In these lines, Lana nods to the little expressions of luxury she allows herself. Usually, one removes jewelry and other valuables before swimming, but leaving them on presents a subtle show of one‚Äôs pride or personal wealth, a common theme throughout Lana‚Äôs musical aesthetic.

In the first line of Verse 1, Lana continues this theme, painting a picture of getting all dressed up to visit everyday places like the market or kids' swimming pools."]]), ('Under the chemtrails over the country club', [['Here, Lana references chemtrails, the colloquially-named condensation trails left in the sky by high-flying aircrafts, which are also the subject of a popular conspiracy theory. While scientists generally agree that such patterns are formed by the breakage of moisture in the atmosphere combined with various gases from aircraft exhaust, conspiracy theorists think that they contain chemical or biological agents used nefariously by the government; hence, chemtrails.

Referencing them directly in her lyrics is a personification of this attitude of being ‚Äúblissfully aware‚Äù as she turns a conspiracy into simply something that is pretty to look at.



Contrails, or chemtrails


Country clubs are private, member-only clubs that offer golf, dining, and other entertaining facilities. They can be exclusive and luxurious, exuding wealth and leisure.']]), ('I‚Äôm on the run with you, my sweet love', [['With this first line, Lana sets the mood for an evocative, minimalist track with a production similar to that of her last album, Norman Fucking Rockwell!, but with a theme that harkens back to those of romance and escapism she‚Äôs been exploring since her debut album Born to Die.

This time, however, the tone and production takes a significantly different twist. Here, Lana sounds less reckless, with a coyer, more mature, and contemplative tone.

Throughout the previously mentioned albums, Lana paints herself as a careless and dependent woman, running from man to man and struggling on finding true love. In ‚ÄúChemtrails‚Äù, Lana expresses her happiness and her freedom.

For example, in ‚ÄúDiet Mountain Dew‚Äù, Lana expresses the fragility of her relationship by asking a question:

Never was there ever a girl so pretty
Do you think we‚Äôll be in love forever?
Do you think we‚Äôll be in love?

In ‚ÄúChemtrails‚Äù, Lana expresses her happiness and her freedom. She also references living in the moment and being with those you love, whoever that may be.']]), ('Nobody‚Äôs son, nobody‚Äôs daughter', [['This line may refer to Lana‚Äôs 2012 track ‚ÄúBody Electric‚Äù, where she sings:

Elvis is my daddy
Marilyn‚Äôs my mother

This also ties back to her earlier song ‚ÄúRide‚Äù, where Lana appears free, but uncertain. Here, however, on ‚ÄúChemtrails‚Äù, Lana may be moving on from that state of mind, fully accepting all aspects of her freedom and being able to maintain it even in a relationship.

At the start of the song, Lana sings ‚ÄúI‚Äôm on the run, with you my sweet love‚Äù so being ‚Äúnobody‚Äôs son, nobody‚Äôs daughter‚Äù could allude that she is on the run, leaving her old life as Lizzy Grant.']]), ('There‚Äôs nothing wrong contemplating God', [['Throughout Del Rey‚Äôs music, there are many conflicting ideas to do with religion and God.

In this lyric, Del Rey defends herself, saying

There‚Äôs nothing wrong with contemplating God

For example, on the 9th track of her 5th studio album Lust for Life, ‚ÄúCoachella ‚Äì Woodstock in My Mind‚Äù, Del Rey mentions many ideas about meeting Jesus.

I‚Äôd trade it all for a stairway to heaven (A stairway, stairway to heaven)
I‚Äôd take my time for the climb up to the top of it (A stairway)
I‚Äôd trade the fame and the fortune and the legend (A stairway)
I‚Äôd give it all away if you give me just one day to ask Him one question
I‚Äôd give it all away if you give me just one day to ask Him one question

Lana shows herself to be selfless ‚Äì proving herself to be willing to sacrifice everything she has to ask God just one question.

And on ‚ÄúDiet Mountain Dew‚Äù, from Born To Die, Del Rey says:

Let‚Äôs take Jesus off the dashboard
Got enough on His mind

Often people have Jesus figures in their car dashboards to remind them that God is watching over them. Lana wants to remove this so she‚Äôs not reminded how far she has strayed from a moral path in life.

In addition, Lana was raised Roman Catholic by her parents. In a 2012 interview with The Telegraph, she mentions having a struggle with her belief and spirituality:

When I was very young I was sort of floored by the fact that my mother and my father and everyone I knew was going to die one day, and myself too. I had a sort of a philosophical crisis. I couldn‚Äôt believe that we were mortal. For some reason that knowledge sort of overshadowed my experience. I was unhappy for some time. I got into a lot of trouble. I used to drink a lot. That was a hard time in my life.

Throughout much of her music, due to her teenage years, Lana Del Rey speaks to her conflict with God and how on one hand she believes God is real and exists, but on other she accepts that God may be dead. She, especially in ‚ÄúChemtrails Over the Country Club‚Äù, is always having a conflict with her ideals or values and the values of those around her. Many may feel that her disbelieving in God is terrible, while others may be saying her belief in God is terrible. By saying ‚ÄúThere‚Äôs nothing wrong in contemplating God‚Äù, Lana opens the door to personal reflection and thought.']]), ('White picket', [['After World War II, cookie cutter houses and mass produced housing developments like Levittowns began popping up across the U.S. The features of these developments and homes, like white picket fences, became iconic symbols of the middle-class white American domestic life. Lana references white picket fences to show the listener what she wants: her American dream of domesticity.']])]
